			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Pulling in Riftseekers - Fire and Ice<a name="71661"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 30 04 10:40 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>To the higher end bard, most of this is old news but for the up and coming bard who might be new to the zone, Here are some survivial tips.
<br />

<br />
<u><b>Pulling in Fire</b></u>
<br />
Depending on your server, Fire *AKA Pyrilen side* often camped more but still requires patience and general experience at what camp you're at. As a general rule of thumb, Bellows pulling is frowned upon unless splitting a particular mob. Why? these mobs run FAST and since you dont' have selos indoors, they do run faster than you.
<br />
Ok for starters, you have Pyrilen Guards, Flameshards and Fireblades as the Warriors versions. Random spawns of these mobs can have a nasty 1500-2000pnt AE stun that has a good range.  And others proc a nasty 45 second Dot that does 750hp per tick.  These are few so you shouldn't worry about those.  When pulling, I generally like to get at near max Harmony of Sound (HoS) length when possible and tag em.  Whenever possible I dart around a corner to get an early head start. Depending on the distance back to camp, I generaly have enough time to cast Requime of Time or Snare.  I say &quot;or&quot; because if your good and know the route back, Snare won't be nessicary.  If you did cast Snare and it landed, slow it and then hightail it back to camp.
<br />
The next set of Pyrilen's are the Cinderhealers .  These can be the bane of your exsistance if your not careful.  The healers I would suggest HoS'ing, Snaring, Despelling THEN slowing.  They have self buffs that can increase their hp up to a few K and sometimes they cast a selfbuff giving them a Damage shield and proc.  Yes I said Proc.  Its a DD only but can wittle your tank down a few K if it lands.  Most don't see this proc since the mob is generally casting.  Plus these mobs also can Gate. Not fun.
<br />
The final set of Pyrilen's are the Flamecharmers. Probably the one mob you need to be worried about the most if were'nt already having a hard enough time as it is.  The reason why?, They haste themselves AND the other mobs around them.  When you have a fully hasted Pyrilen than can hit for 1300hp and up to 12 times in 1 second with a stun, you will feel the pain if they happen to catch you.  I've personaly witnessed my group wipe to a single Flamecharmer due to slow not landing fast enough.  Pulling these mobs requires several type of tactics that alter depending on your style.  If you don't mind burning a FM, double pull this mob with HOS then Fade, Snare then Despell and Slow.  Another method is casting Despell, then HOS then snare and hope your still alive to make it back to camp.  Note, If a flamecharmer is up on Track, be aware that they do cast haste on Roaming mobs and be especially warey if that Flamecharmer is a roamer himself.
<br />

<br />
<u><b>Pulling in Ice</b></u>
<br />
Ice &quot;tends&quot; to be less camped than the Fire side but no less dangerous.  The same pulling rules apply to the fire side, HoS, Slow or Snare, then Despell.  Bellows pulling is again frowned upon because of the speed at which these mobs run.  Gelidran Frostblades and Guards are your warrior type mobs but random spawns can have a nasty 1500-2000hp stun AE proc. The other random cast is the dreaded 1 Min mez.  This is often the reason why groups won't camp the Ice side because of this nasty random cast.  Even the most well established groups have wiped due to the mob casting this near unresistable mez on the tank and DPS only then feeling free to slaughter the clerics and casters.  Because of the nature of the Mez and its memory wiping ablities, often its the tanks and DPS left alive.  
<br />
But there is a ray of hope with this Mezing mob, but it requires patience and a bit of general knowledge about how to fight him.  When you pull this mob, he generally insta-casts the 1 min mez on you.  This gives you time to regroup an prepare for the fight.  Tip: if your tank is an SK, have him DoT himself with a lower level DoT in attempt to break mez should it land. Don't have an SK? don't worry as casting Amp, Voice of the Serpant (which all bards at this level should have by now) and Veeshans to max out your Cold resists.  During the Pull, Veeshans should be going and generaly the mez will get resisted (if your lucky).  This fight won't be easy but singing Veeshans and Amp should be your main priority.  1 land of mez will incapistate a member and that could be your cleric.  All other songs should be avoided and kept out of rotation since this is an abnormal fight.
<br />
Once I learned the general strategies of how to fight against the random Mezing mob, I have yet to lose a group member since.
<br />

<br />
Again, these are general tips and strategies for surviving Rift based on my experiences.  I welcome any an additional tips and information that I might of left out or you feel that should be added.  Best of luck fellow Performers.</span></td>
