			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Pulling in Riftseekers - Fire and Ice<a name="71941"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 7 05 3:08 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>dsavereide,
<br />
<i>I'm puzzled by your spell order. &quot;HoS'ing, Snaring, Despelling THEN slowing.&quot; Aren't you dispelling HoS and snare this way? I start with dispell, hos then slow on the short pulls and dispell, snare on the long pulls, hos as it approaches camp.</i> 
<br />

<br />
Glad you asked that, no I didn't make a mistake when I posted that order.  Again, this is the way &quot;I&quot; do it and the way I recommend.  Generally you are pulling mobs that are farther away that you are so this set up works. On the Cinderhealers and Firecharmers, I <b>HOS</b>, then <b>Snare</b> because now I have a Slow moving mob coming after me.  I then Despell to get rid of its self buffs like Rune V, Haste and the ever popular Damage shield.  Then I can Requim them and haul a$ back to camp.  Rarely does my HOS get despelled on these two mobs but when it does, so what. I still have a snared mob for the remaining seconds so I can just HOS again, snare if need be and Requim.
<br />

<br />
I realize it doesn't make much sense on paper, but when you encounter the mobs enough times, you will see the patern in why I use my particular method.  I'm not saying its perfect by any means, but its the one which works best for me. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
